    {
      "id": "https://www.openculture.com/2026/04/why-animals-look-so-strange-in-medieval-manuscripts.html",
      "url": "https://www.openculture.com/2026/04/why-animals-look-so-strange-in-medieval-manuscripts.html",
      "title": "[Open Culture] Why Animals Look So Strange in Medieval Manuscripts",
      "content_html": "<img src=\"https://cdn8.openculture.com/2026/04/21231846/Screenshot-2026-04-21-at-11.19.17-PM-1024x557.png\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n<img src=\"https://cdn8.openculture.com/2026/04/21231846/Screenshot-2026-04-21-at-11.19.17-PM-1024x557.png\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n<img src=\"https://cdn8.openculture.com/2026/04/21231846/Screenshot-2026-04-21-at-11.19.17-PM-1024x557.png\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n<img src=\"https://cdn8.openculture.com/2026/04/21231846/Screenshot-2026-04-21-at-11.19.17-PM-1024x557.png\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\nThough you may not hear it every day, chimera&#160;remains an evocative word, perhaps even more so for its rarity. It descends from the Greek Khimaira, literally “year-old she-goat,” the name of a mythical fire-breathing creature with a caprine body, sure enough, but also the head of a lion and the tail of a dragon. Today [&#8230;]",
      "date_published": "2026-04-22T09:00:14+00:00",
      "authors": [
        {
          "name": "Open Culture",
          "url": "https://www.openculture.com/"
        }
      ],
      "image": "https://cdn8.openculture.com/2026/04/21231846/Screenshot-2026-04-21-at-11.19.17-PM-1024x557.png"
